<td valign=top bgcolor=d1c3b5 class=headings><font color=#000000>Comment</font></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ufritzdarkweaver.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Fritz Darkweaver</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 11<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(10/8/01 1:54:11 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm9.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=11.topic&index=13>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_question_mark.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: Some misconceptions here...</span><hr size=1> It sounds to me like you're not a power gamer (at least with that system).  Don't take that as an insult... it's not meant to be one.  I'm not a power gamer either.<br>
<br>
I just went through a BIOS chip burnout, so I needed to upgrade my system.  Was running an Athlon 650 on an aBIT motherboard with a GeForce 32 DDR Vid card.  Schwammmmmmmi system at the time, but a bit underpowered, now.<br>
<br>
So, after calling around (and keeping in mind that if I lost the BIOS chip, the power supply probably is having problems, so I might as well replace motherboard, chip, and power supply) I decided to be lazy and buy a shell (all of the above, surrounded by a case).<br>
<br>
Checking around, I could have gotten a Duron 850 for $50.  Motherboard for that would be around $35.  That's from retail in my area, as I don't like ordering over the web if I can help it (bad experiences).<br>
<br>
What I ended up doing was being REALLY lazy and buying a T-bird 1GHz chip on a pre-configured generic motherboard with a case and power-supply already hooked up for $350.  Might not have been the best price in the world, but it wasn't bad.  Two sticks of 256 cost me $100 (retail, but still good) so for $450 I've got what amounts to a brand new system.  <br>
<br>
Look around.  You can move your old hard drive(s) to a shell system along with your motherboard and associated pc cards, for a ridiculously low amount of money.<br>
<br>
Just my 2 cents.<br>
<br>
